Gunfire detection systems see renewed interest after recent Las Vegas mass shooting
There's growing interest in gunfire detection technology by major police agencies around the nation with systems such as ShotSpotter.
AmberBox, a maker of a system to detect indoor active shooter incidents, sees "greater urgency" for the tech since the Las Vegas mass shooting.
The Army used Raytheon's Boomerang system in battlefields to find sniper locations and now casinos are showing interest in the technology.
Military funding helped develop SENTRI, which detect gunfire and can be set to recognize glass breaking.
